# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation

Successfully implemented Vercel Speed Insights for the Connect Six game application.

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed Dependencies
- Added `@vercel/speed-insights` package to the project
- Package version installed: Latest version available via npm

### 2. Modified Files

**src/App.jsx**
- Added import statement: `import { SpeedInsights } from '@vercel/speed-insights/react';`
- Added `<SpeedInsights />` component at the end of the main App component's return statement
- The component is placed just before the closing div tag to ensure it tracks all page interactions

**package.json & package-lock.json**
- Updated to include the new `@vercel/speed-insights` dependency

## Implementation Details

This is a React application built with Vite. Following the Vercel Speed Insights documentation for React applications, I implemented the Speed Insights tracking by:

1. Using the React-specific package (`@vercel/speed-insights/react`)
2. Adding the `<SpeedInsights />` component to the main App component
3. Placing it at the root level to track all routes and interactions

The component is a wrapper around the tracking script that provides seamless integration with React applications and will automatically:
- Track Core Web Vitals (CWV) metrics
- Monitor page performance
- Send data to Vercel's Speed Insights dashboard once deployed

## Testing & Verification

✅ Build completed successfully (`npm run build`)
✅ No new linting errors introduced by these changes
✅ Application structure preserved
✅ Lock files updated correctly

## Next Steps

After deployment to Vercel:
1. Enable Speed Insights in the Vercel dashboard (Project → Speed Insights → Enable)
2. The `/_vercel/speed-insights/script.js` route will be automatically added
3. Performance metrics will start appearing in the Speed Insights dashboard after users visit the site

## Notes

- The implementation follows Vercel's recommended pattern for React applications
- Pre-existing linting warnings in the codebase were not addressed as they are unrelated to this implementation
- The SpeedInsights component requires no additional configuration for basic usage
